    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogies. To answer your question directly, it's possible that the squeal is caused by dust or debris accumulating on the brake pads or rotors, which can be easily cleaned off. However, if the brake pads are worn down, it's likely that they need to be replaced.\n\nA good rule of thumb is to check the brake pads and rotors for wear by looking for the following:\n\n* Brake pads that are thinner than 1/8 inch (3 mm) or have excessive wear on the friction surface\n* Rotors that are warped, scored, or excessively worn down\n* A brake pad wear indicator (a small metal marker) that's visible through the brake pad\n\nIf your brake pads or rotors are in good condition, a simple cleaning or lubrication might resolve the issue. But if they're worn out, it's time to replace them. It's always best to have a professional mechanic inspect your brakes to determine the cause of the squeal and recommend any necessary repairs.",
